        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often do fire extinguishers need to be inspected in Chula Vista, CA?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Monthly visual inspections by building staff, annual professional inspections by a licensed technician, 6-year internal examinations, and 12-year hydrostatic testing per NFPA 10 and the California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR).</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does a fire extinguisher inspection cost in Chula Vista, CA?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Annual inspections in the San Diego County (South Bay) typically cost $16–$42 per unit. 6-year internal examinations run $26–$58. 12-year hydrostatic tests cost $34–$75. Volume discounts apply for 20+ units.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who can inspect fire extinguishers in Chula Vista, CA?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Monthly visual checks by trained staff. Annual, 6-year, and 12-year service by a licensed technician. California requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold an OSFM license from the California State Fire Marshal's Office. Verify licensing at osfm.fire.ca.gov before scheduling service.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What are the most common fire extinguisher violations in Chula Vista?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The most common violations cited by the Chula Vista Fire Department include: Missing Class K extinguishers in Otay Ranch and Millenia restaurant commercial kitchens; Missing Class B coverage in Otay Mesa industrial and import/export facility storage areas.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does Chula Vista require fire extinguishers in all commercial buildings?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. The California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR) requires portable fire extinguishers in all commercial, industrial, and multi-family residential buildings. Type, size, and placement depend on occupancy classification and hazard level per NFPA 10.</p></div></div>
